<a href="https://towardsdatascience.com/cosine-similarity-how-does-it-measure-the-similarity-maths-behind-and-usage-in-python-50ad30aad7db">Expanding this out</a> gives us the formula for <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cosine_similarity">Cosine Similarity</a>.

<div class="paragraph">
<p>\$similarity(vec{A},vec{B}) = \cos(\theta) = \frac{\vec{A}\cdot\vec{B}}{||\vec{A}\||\cdot||\vec{B}||\$</p>
</div>

This formula works for dimensions higher than 2 or 3, though it is hard to visualize. However, <a href="https://projector.tensorflow.org/">it can be visualized to some extent</a>.
It is common for vectors in AI/ML applications to have hundreds or even thousands of dimensions.
